have a comprehensive picture. Let me compile the full review.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Review: PR #415 — Add OpenCode agent support\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nThis PR adds OpenCode as a third supported coding agent (alongside Claude Code and Gemini CLI) across 18 files / ~2,169 lines. It includes an embedded TypeScript plugin, hook lifecycle handling, transcript parsing, condensation, explain scoping, and summarization support.\\n\\n### Comparison with Other Open PRs\\n\\n| | **#415 (this)** | **#341 (adrianmg)** | **#220 (ammarateya)** | **#315 (MementoMori123)** | **#257 (Avyukth)** |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| **Files** | 18 | 22 | 11 | 6 | 19 |\\n| **Approach** | Embedded TS plugin → `entire hooks opencode` | Same plugin approach | Plugin approach + `opencode export` | No hooks (agent-managed) | Combined OpenCode + Codex + shared pipeline |\\n| **Transcript** | Plugin writes JSON from in-memory + SDK fallback | Plugin writes JSONL to tmpdir | Transcript reconstruction from `~/.local/share/opencode/storage/` | N/A (passthrough) | Git-status-based (no transcript parsing) |\\n| **Hooks** | 5 (session-start, session-end, turn-start, turn-end, compaction) | 4 (session-start, user-prompt-submit, stop, task) | 4 (prompt-submit, stop, session events) | 0 (SupportsHooks=false) | 3 (session-created, session-busy, session-idle) |\\n| **Tests** | Unit + summarize tests | 61 unit + 23 integration | Limited (transcript_test) | Registry test only | Unit tests for Codex + OpenCode |\\n| **Status** | Current branch | Maintainer asked to wait for #281 | Draft, told to wait for #281 | Told to wait for #281 | Told to wait for #281 |\\n\\n**Key observation:** All open PRs have been told to wait for the agent interface refactor (#281). This PR seems to be from a maintainer (peyton-alt, on the same `feat/add-opencode` branch as PR #415), so it may be the \\\"official\\\" implementation.\\n\\n### Correctness vs OpenCode Plugin Docs\\n\\n**Events used vs available:**\\n\\nThe plugin docs list these session events: `session.created`, `session.compacted`, `session.deleted`, `session.diff`, `session.error`, `session.idle`, `session.status`, `session.updated`. Plus message events: `message.updated`, `message.part.updated`.\\n\\nThis PR uses:\\n- `session.created` — correct\\n- `message.updated` — correct (accumulates message metadata)\\n- `message.part.updated` — correct (accumulates parts per message)\\n- `session.idle` — correct (turn-end)\\n- `session.compacted` — correct\\n- `session.deleted` — correct (session-end)\\n\\nMissing events that *could* be useful:\\n- `session.error` — not handled. If the session errors, no final transcript is written. Consider at least writing what's in memory.\\n- `session.diff` — not handled (reasonable, this is for UI diffing)\\n- `tool.execute.before` / `tool.execute.after` — not used, but could provide more accurate file-modification tracking\\n\\n**Tool names (FileModificationTools):**\\n\\nThe PR defines: `edit_file`, `write`, `write_file`, `create_file`, `patch`\\n\\nOpenCode's actual tool names from source: `edit`, `write`, `patch`\\n\\n**Issue: `edit_file`, `write_file`, `create_file` don't exist in OpenCode.** The real tool names are `edit`, `write`, and `patch`. The current list appears to be borrowed from Claude Code's tool names. Since the plugin writes tool call data using OpenCode's part format, only the actual OpenCode tool names would appear. This means `edit` and `write` will match (they're in the list as `write`), but `edit_file` is wrong — the real tool is just `edit`. You'd miss edits.\\n\\n**Transcript storage path:**\\n\\nThe plugin stores transcripts at `~/.opencode/sessions/entire/<sanitized-path>/<sessionId>.json`. This is a custom location (not OpenCode's native `~/.local/share/opencode/storage/`), which is fine since the plugin controls the writes. The Go side mirrors this with `SanitizePathForOpenCode()`. PR #220 took a different approach (reading from OpenCode's native storage), but this PR's approach is more reliable since it controls the format.\\n\\n### Code Quality\\n\\n**Strengths:**\\n1. Clean separation of concerns: `types.go`, `hooks.go`, `lifecycle.go`, `transcript.go`, `opencode.go`, `plugin.go`\\n2. Implements all relevant interfaces: `Agent`, `HookSupport`, `HookHandler`, `TranscriptAnalyzer`, `TokenCalculator`\\n3. Comprehensive tests for transcript parsing, chunking, reassembly, and lifecycle events\\n4. The plugin's dual-path transcript writing (SDK API with in-memory fallback for shutdown) is clever and robust\\n5. Condensation, explain, and summarize paths are all wired up\\n6. Proper `go:embed` for the plugin template\\n7. Good nolint annotations with explanations\\n\\n**Issues:**\\n\\n1. **FileModificationTools list is wrong** (as noted above). Should be `edit`, `write`, `patch` per OpenCode's source. Remove `edit_file`, `write_file`, `create_file`.\\n\\n2. **`extractFilePathFromInput` key names may not match OpenCode's tool args.** OpenCode's `edit` tool takes `file_path` (confirmed via the docs plugin example), but `write` takes `file_path` too. The keys `file`, `filename` are speculative — verify against actual OpenCode tool arg schemas.\\n\\n3. **Plugin `callHook` uses `echo ${json} | cmd`.** BunShell's `${}` interpolation is injection-safe (it quotes automatically), so this is OK. But the pattern of piping through echo means very large payloads could hit shell argument limits. Consider using `Bun.write` to a temp file + `< file` redirect for the turn-end hook (which includes the largest payloads).\\n\\n4. **`session.deleted` cleanup clears ALL in-memory stores.** If OpenCode supports concurrent sessions (the docs mention multi-session capability), deleting one session would wipe the in-memory state for another. The stores should be keyed by session ID.\\n\\n5. **`explain.go` has unreachable code.** After the `switch` block on lines 2011-2017, line 2018 still has `return transcript.SliceFromLine(...)`. The `case agent.AgentTypeClaudeCode, agent.AgentTypeUnknown:` + the default covers everything, making the trailing return dead code. Same issue in `transcriptOffset()`.\\n\\n6. **`setup.go` `removeAgentHooks` is still hardcoded per-agent** rather than iterating the registry. PR #341 noted this and refactored it to use `agent.All()`. Consider doing the same to prevent this from growing with each agent.\\n\\n7. **`FormatResumeCommand` returns `\\\"opencode --session \\\" + sessionID`** — verify this is the actual OpenCode CLI flag. The OpenCode repo doesn't seem to have a `--session` flag documented in its README.\\n\\n8. **No integration tests.** PR #341 had 23 integration tests. This PR only has unit tests for the opencode package and summarize tests. The hook lifecycle (session-start → turn-start → turn-end → session-end with checkpoint creation/rewind) isn't integration-tested.\\n\\n9. **`DetectPresence` falls back to `\\\".\\\"` when `RepoRoot()` fails** rather than propagating the error. This could give false positives if run outside a repo.\\n\\n### Minor Observations\\n\\n- The `extractGenericToolDetail` rename from `extractGeminiToolDetail` is a nice touch for reuse\\n- The `session.compacted` → \\\"compaction\\\" hook is forward-thinking (context window compaction is unique to OpenCode)\\n- `IsPreview() = true` is appropriate since OpenCode's plugin API may still change\\n- Tests properly handle `t.Parallel()` vs `t.Chdir()` per the CLAUDE.md guidelines\\n\\n### Recommendations\\n\\n1. **Fix `FileModificationTools`** to match OpenCode's actual tool names: `edit`, `write`, `patch`\\n2. **Add multi-session safety** to the plugin's in-memory stores (key by session ID)\\n3. **Handle `session.error`** in the plugin (write whatever's in memory before cleanup)\\n4. **Remove dead code** after the switch statements in `explain.go`\\n5. **Consider registry-based iteration** in `removeAgentHooks` instead of adding another hardcoded block\\n6. **Verify `--session` flag** for `FormatResumeCommand`\\n7