iCCg6aZyFZAvGM\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Right — Entire doesn't store anything outside the repo *of its own*. But it does **read** from outside the repo — specifically from each agent's *own* session directories:\\n\\n| Agent | `GetSessionDir` path | Whose directory? |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Claude Code | `~/.claude/projects/<sanitized>/` | Claude Code's own dir |\\n| Gemini CLI | `~/.gemini/tmp/<hash>/chats/` | Gemini CLI's own dir |\\n| **OpenCode** | `~/.opencode/sessions/entire/<sanitized>/` | **Invented by this PR** |\\n\\nClaude Code and Gemini CLI both read transcripts from directories that **those agents themselves create and manage**. Entire just reads what's already there.\\n\\nOpenCode is the odd one out — it doesn't write transcripts to disk at all (it uses SQLite). So this PR invents a new path *and* has the plugin write to it. The problem is it squats on `~/.opencode/` as if it belongs to OpenCode, when it's actually Entire creating and owning that data.\\n\\nIf the pattern is \\\"read from the agent's own session directory,\\\" this breaks it. A more consistent approach would be to either:\\n- Store inside the repo (e.g., `.entire/opencode-sessions/`) to match Entire's \\\"everything in the repo\\\" pattern\\n- Or use a clearly Entire-owned path outside the repo if there's a good reason not to (e.g., `~/.entire/opencode-transcripts/`)\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":707,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":108697,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":707},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYHS54LaoHNmNyQxykdeo\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"62d17607-1c1b-487d-9a0c-578c562a1037\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T12:32:38.233Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"62d17607-1c1b-487d-9a0c-578c562a1037\",\"isSidechain\":false,